results.notes:
Fruiting in our nitrogen rich raised bed soil/mulch at the Yauger park community garden.
Rusty orange brown slightly conical dunce cap stature.

Cheilocystidia: Lecythiform(like a squat bowling pin/Russian doll shape).
Spores: Large, Ellipsoid/ovoid with a distinct apical pore. Rusty orange colored in KOH.
Spore Print: rusty brown.
Spores from spore print also mounted in KOH. Spores from spore print in KOH deeper orange toned than ejected spores analyzed from gill mount but all features obviously identical(apical pore, ellipsoid/ovoid, etc). See images of work/process included.
Dehydrated all specimens thoroughly and bagged for herbarium collection/genetic record.

The cap color and texture, the color of the mature pores and the pseudo-reticulated pattern formed by the scabers are the feature I associated with L. albellum, which is a highly variable species. The fruitbody was sectioned at the foray and there was no staining anywhere in the cut flesh.
This collection was preserved.

Older one was ambur, wrinkled and dry, gills were wavy and dull, opaque white, and had a few of the yellow granuals on the portion of the stipe that was underground.

No spore print from either unfortunately ::/
